{{Infobox person | name = | image = | caption = Carol Ruckdeschel standing next to a male loggerhead turtle shell |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|12|03|mf=y}} |birth_place = [[Rochester, New York]] | residence = [[Cumberland Island, Georgia]] | occupation = Biologist, naturalist, and environmental activist | years_active = 1971–present | spouse = Charles Wharton (second marriage, in Ruckdeschel's 20s) }} '''Carol Ruckdeschel''' is a [[biologist]], [[naturalist]], [[environmental activist]]<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=John McPhee|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1973/04/28/travels-in-georgia|title=Travels in Georgia|last=McPhee|first=John|date=April 28, 1973|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref> and [[author]]. As a [[Cumberland Island]] resident, she was involved in the creation and preservation of [[Cumberland Island National Seashore]].<ref name="Dilsaver2004">{{cite book|last=Dilsaver|first=Lary M.|title=Cumberland Island National Seashore: A History of Conservation Conflict|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wfjrDw09GaEC&pg=PA128|accessdate=23 September 2014|year=2004|publisher=University of Virginia Press|isbn=9780813922683|pages=128–}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| edition = First | publisher = Grove Press| isbn = 9780802122582| last = Harlan| first = Will| title = Untamed: the wildest woman in America and the fight for Cumberland Island| location = New York| date = 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Blqackmun| first = Susie| title = The Naturalist For 16 Hours A Day, Seven Days A Week, Biologist Carol Ruckdeschel Lives Breathes, Studies And Defends A Tiny Barrier Island Just Over The Florida Border. It's Not Just A Job, It's A Way Of Life That She Has Followed For Nearly 20 Years| accessdate = 2015-04-19| date = 1991-06-09| url = http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-06-09/news/9106071106_1_cumberland-island-stomach-contents-barrier-island}}</ref> She is the subject of the book ''[[Untamed: The Wildest Woman in America and the Fight for Cumberland Island]]'' by Will Harlan.
She does ongoing research on [[sea turtles]]<ref>Sea Turtles of the Atlantic and Gulf Coasts of the United States. Carol Ruckdeschel. 2006</ref> and endangered and extinct species around the Georgia coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/the-bone-collectors-37287990/|title=History, Travel, Arts, Science, People, Places - Smithsonian|publisher=Smithsonianmag.com|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>
Her residence on the north part of [[Cumberland Island]] is currently owned by The [[National Park Service]], on the condition of her remaining there until her death.
