[[File:Rapsfeld 2007.jpg|thumb|300px|Colza cultivation in Germany]]
'''Colza oil''' or '''colza''' is a [[non-drying oil]] obtained from the seeds of [[rapeseed]] (''Brassica napus'' subsp. ''napus''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_i8KAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA204 ''Vegetable substances: materials of manufactures''], [[Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge]], 1833, p. 204-205</ref> [[Synonym (taxonomy)|syn.]] ''Brassica napus'' var. ''oleifera'' Delile, ''Brassica campestris'' subsp. ''napus'' (L.) Hook.f. & T.Anderson.)<ref>[[Rapeseed#cite_note-grin-1|Ref. GRIN]]</ref> Colza is extensively cultivated in [[France]], [[Belgium]], the [[United States of America|United States]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Germany]] and [[Poland]]. In France, especially, the extraction of the [[oil]] is an important industry. In commerce, colza is a traditional [[rapeseed oil]] (with turnip rape oil, sarson oil, toria oil (''[[Brassica rapa]]'' ssp.), and [[Sinapis arvensis|ravison]] oil),<ref>Jan Velíšek, [https://books.google.com/books?id=-IdyAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq="colza" ''The Chemistry of Food''], [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]], 2014, p. 102</ref> to which they are very closely allied in both source and properties. It is a comparatively nonodoriferous oil of a yellow colour, having a [[specific gravity]] varying between 0.912 and 0.920. The cake left after extraction of the oil is a valuable feed ingredient for [[pigs]].

==Uses==
Colza oil is extensively used as a [[lubricant]] for machinery.

Colza oil was used extensively in European domestic lighting before the advent of [[Coal gas|coal (city) gas]] or [[kerosene]]. It was the preferred oil for train pot lamps, and was used for lighting [[Passenger car (rail)|railway coaches]] in the [[United Kingdom]] before [[gas lighting]], and later [[electric lighting]], were adopted. Burned in a [[Carcel burner|Carcel lamp]], it was part of the definition of the French standard measure for [[lighting|illumination]], the [[carcel]], for most of the nineteenth century. In [[lighthouses]], for example in early [[Canada]], colza oil was used before the introduction of [[mineral oil]]. The colza oil was used with the [[Argand burner]] because it was cheaper than [[whale oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccg-gcc.gc.ca/eng/CCG/USQUE_Early_Lights |title=USQUE AD MARE - Early Lights - Canadian Coast Guard |publisher=Ccg-gcc.gc.ca |date=2008-03-31 |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>  Colza was burned to a limited extent in the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2001.05.0289%3Achapter%3D1.23 |first=John W. |last=Mallett |title=How the South got chemicals during the war |journal=Southern Historical Society Papers |volume=31 |page=101}}</ref>

Colza oil was used in Gombault's Caustic Balsam,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racehorseherbal.com/Herbal_Therapies/Liniments/Gombaults/gombaults.html |title=Gombaults |publisher=Racehorseherbal.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-14|quote=Note that the ingredients listed in this link are similar to, but not the same as, the list on the actual bottle.}}</ref> a popular horse and human [[liniment]] at the turn of the 20th century. 

Among the more unusual applications of colza oil is the [[storm oil|calming of choppy seas]], where the oil modifies the [[surface tension]] of the water and rapidly smooths the surface. For this purpose, colza oil was carried in ship's lifeboats. Rescue and recovery operations have been made far less risky in this way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1893/03/04/archives/oil-tested-in-storms-at-sea.html |title=Oil Tested in Storms at Sea |publisher=New York Times |date=1893-03-04 |accessdate=2010-03-14|newspaper=The New York Times }}</ref>

More recently, colza has been cultivated in Europe as an ingredient for [[biodiesel]] fuels, and is the primary source of [[biodiesel]] in Germany.

