A '''photino''' is a hypothetical [[subatomic particle]], the [[fermion]] [[Weakly interacting massive particles|WIMP]] superpartner of the [[photon]] predicted by [[supersymmetry]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v317/n6036/abs/317411a0.html|title=Photinos from cosmic sources|publisher=[[nature.com]]|accessdate=2015-09-24|first=V. J. |last=STENGER|volume=317|issue=6036|doi=10.1038/317411a0|journal=Nature|pages=411–413|bibcode=1985Natur.317..411S}}</ref> It is an example of a [[gaugino]]. Even though no photino has ever been observed so far, it is one of the candidates for the lightest stable particle in the universe.<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date=9 January 1986  |title=Tracking down the missing mass |url=https://books.google.ru/books?id=Ri8kegHjaoYC&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32&dq=Photino+particle&source=bl&ots=l2fYHQEdbW&sig=7QJ2jTs5CxA6ryquVTwCFk8pCnM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEIQ6AEwCGoVChMIhdf8w7ePyAIVh8ByCh2dIAQu#v=onepage&q=Photino%20particle&f=false | journal=[[New Scientist]] |publisher= |volume=|issue=1490 |pages=32 |doi= |access-date=24 September 2015}}</ref> It is proposed that photinos are produced by sources of [[ultra-high-energy cosmic rays]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=STENGER|first1=V. J.|title=Photinos from cosmic sources|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v317/n6036/abs/317411a0.html|website=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|accessdate=16 August 2016|date=3 October 1985|volume=317|issue=6036|doi=10.1038/317411a0|pages=411–413|bibcode=1985Natur.317..411S}}</ref>

==Photino numbers==
Photinos have a [[lepton]] number 0, [[baryon]] number 0, and [[Spin (physics)|spin]] 1/2. With an [[R-parity]] of −1 it is a possible candidate for [[dark matter]]. It mixes with the superpartners of the [[Z boson]] (zino) and the neutral higgs (higgsino) to the [[neutralino]].

