website_ref= |date=May 2010 }} {{Infobox |bodystyle=width:23.5em |title=Verkhoyansk population |label1=[[Russian Census (2010)|2010 Census]] |data1=1,311<ref name="2010Census">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref> |label2=[[Russian Census (2002)|2002 Census]] |data2=1,434<ref name="2002Census">{{ru-pop-ref|2002Census}}</ref> |label3=[[Soviet Census (1989)|1989 Census]] |data3=1,883<ref name="1989Census">{{ru-pop-ref|1989Census}}</ref> |label4=[[Soviet Census (1979)|1979 Census]] |data4=1,709<ref name="1979Census">{{ru-pop-ref|1979Census}}</ref> }} '''Verkhoyansk''' ({{lang-rus|Верхоянск|p=vʲɪrxɐˈjansk}}; {{lang-sah|Верхоянскай}}, ''Verkhoyanskay'') is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|town]] in [[Verkhoyansky District]] of the [[Sakha Republic]], [[Russia]], located on the [[Yana River]] near the [[Arctic Circle]], {{convert|92|km|sp=us}} from [[Batagay]], the [[administrative center]] of the district, and {{convert|675|km|sp=us}} north of [[Yakutsk]], the [[capital city|capital]] of the republic. As of the [[Russian Census (2010)|2010 Census]], its population was&nbsp;1,311.<ref name="2010Census">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref> The town holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness world record]] for the greatest temperature range on Earth: {{convert|105|C-change}}.<ref name="Guinness">http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/greatest-temperature-range-on-earth/</ref>
==History== [[Cossacks]] founded an [[ostrog (fortress)|ostrog]] in 1638,<ref name="gr">{{cite book|title=Энциклопедия Города России|year=2003|publisher=Большая Российская Энциклопедия|location=Moscow|isbn=5-7107-7399-9|page=69}}</ref> {{convert|90|km|sp=us}} southwest of the modern town. The ostrog's name "Verkhoyansky", roughly translating from Russian as ''the town on the Upper Yana'', derived from its geographical location on the upper reaches of the [[Yana River]]. In 1775, it was moved to the left bank of the Yana River to facilitate tax collection. It was granted town status in 1817.{{citation needed|date=May 2010}} Between the 1860s and 1917, the town was a place of political exile, with some of the more prominent exiles including the [[Poles|Polish]] writer [[Wacław Sieroszewski]], as well as Bolshevik revolutionaries [[Ivan Babushkin]] and [[Viktor Nogin]].
==Administrative and municipal status== As an [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|inhabited locality]], Verkhoyansk is classified as a town under district jurisdiction.<ref name="SakhaR_admlist">''Registry of the Administrative-Territorial Divisions of the Sakha Republic''</ref> Within the [[subdivisions of Russia#Administrative divisions|framework of administrative divisions]], it is incorporated within [[Verkhoyansky District]] as the '''[[Town of district significance|Town]] of Verkhoyansk'''.<ref name="SakhaR_admlist" /> As a [[subdivisions of Russia#Municipal divisions|municipal division]], the Town of Verkhoyansk is incorporated within Verkhoyansky Municipal District as '''Verkhoyansk Urban Settlement'''.<ref name="Ref531">Law #173-Z #353-III</ref>
== Economy and infrastructure == There is a [[inland port|river port]], an [[airport]], a [[fur]]-collecting depot, and the center of a [[reindeer]]-raising area. It is also home to the [http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g2541140-d2622677-Reviews-Pole_of_Cold_District_Museum_of_Local_Lore-Verkhoyansk_Sakha_Yakutia_Republic_Fa.html Pole of Cold Museum.]
== Geography ==
=== Climate === Verkhoyansk is notable chiefly for its exceptionally low winter temperatures and some of the greatest temperature differences on Earth between summer and winter. Average monthly temperatures range from {{convert|-45.4|C}} in January to {{convert|+16.5|C}} in July. Mean monthly temperatures are below freezing from October through April and exceed {{convert|+10|C}} from June through August, with the intervening months of May and September constituting very short transitional seasons. Verkhoyansk has an extreme [[subarctic climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification|Köppen]] ''Dfd'') dominated much of the year by [[anticyclone|high pressure]]. This has the effect of cutting off the region from warming influences in winter and together with a lack of cloud cover leads to extensive heat losses during the cooler months.
Verkhoyansk is one of the places considered the northern [[Pole of Cold]], the others being [[Oymyakon]], located 629 km (391 miles) away by air, and [[Delyankir]]. The lowest temperature recorded there, in February 1892, was {{convert|-67.6|C|1}}, recorded on February 5 and 7.<ref name="Stepanova">{{cite web|author=N. A. Stepanova |title=On the Lowest Temperatures on Earth|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/086/mwr-086-01-0006.pdf}}</ref><ref name="Burt">Weather Underground - The Coldest Places on Earth https://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/the-coldest-places-on-earth</ref> This was formerly the coldest officially recorded temperature in the [[Northern Hemisphere]]. However, on February 6, 1933, the temperature at Oymyakon reached {{convert|-67.7|C|1}}, just barely exceeding Verkhoyansk's record.<ref name="Stepanova"/><ref name="Burt"/> Only Antarctica has recorded [[Lowest_temperature_recorded_on_Earth|lower temperatures]] than Oymyakon or Verkhoyansk: the lowest directly recorded temperature at ground level is {{convert|-89.2|C}}, recorded at the [[Vostok Station]] in [[Antarctica]] on July&nbsp;21, 1983.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Weather & Climate Extremes|url=http://wmo.asu.edu/#global|publisher=World Meteorological Organization|accessdate=December 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World: Lowest Temperature |url=http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]] |accessdate=December 23, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616025722/http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |archivedate=June 16, 2010 |df= }}</ref>, and a temperature of {{convert|-93.2|C}} was recorded via satellite observations at the [[East Antarctic Plateau]] in [[Antarctica]] on August 10, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Coldest Place in the World|url=https://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2013/09dec_coldspot|publisher=NASA|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>
In this area, [[inversion (meteorology)|temperature inversions]] consistently form in winter due to the extremely cold and dense air of the [[Siberian High]] pooling in deep hollows, so that temperatures increase rather than decrease with higher altitude. In Verkhoyansk it sometimes happens that the average minimum temperatures for January, February, and December are below {{convert|−50|C}}. Oymyakon and Verkhoyansk are the only two permanently populated places in the world that have recorded temperatures below {{convert|-60.0|C}} every day of January.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}
In June, July, and August, daytime temperatures over {{convert|+30|C}} are not uncommon. The warmest month on record is July 2001, at {{convert|+21.9|C}}.<ref>GHCN monthly climate data; Goddard Institute of Space Studies record for Verhojansk 1885-2010</ref> The average annual temperature for Verkhoyansk is {{convert|-14.5|C}}. On July&nbsp;25, 1988, Verkhoyansk recorded a temperature of {{convert|+37.3|C}}, yielding a temperature range of {{convert|105|C-change}} based on reliable records, which is the greatest temperature range in the world. Oymyakon, Delyankir, and Yakutsk are the only other places in the world with a temperature range higher than {{convert|100|C-change}}. Verkhoyansk has never recorded a temperature above freezing between November&nbsp;10 and March&nbsp;14.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weather and Climate - Climate Monitor: The weather in Verkhoyansk|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24266&month=11&year=2013|publisher=www.pogodaiklimat.ru|accessdate=December 25, 2013|language=Russian}} Daily records on the right of the page; December–March records can be accessed via buttons at the bottom of the page.</ref>
Verkhoyansk has a dry climate with little rainfall or snowfall: the average annual [[precipitation]] is {{convert|180|mm|sp=us}}. Although no month can be described as truly wet, there are strong seasonal differences in precipitation, with the summer being much wetter than the winter. Winter precipitation is extremely light, largely because of the dominance of high pressure at this time of year.
